"Muñoz I., Peral J., Antonio Ayllón J., Malato S., Passarinho P., Domènech X.","Life cycle assessment of a coupled solar photocatalytic-biological process for wastewater treatment",2006,"Water Research","40","19",,"3533","3540",,,10.1016/j.watres.2006.08.001,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33749682236&partnerID=40&md5=e4443cd83f82f966f7a1416b0a391283","Departament de Química, Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona, 08193 Bellaterra, Barcelona, Spain; Plataforma Solar de Almería-CIEMAT, Carretera Senes km 4, 04200 Tabernas, Almería, Spain; Instituto Nacional de Engenharia, Tecnologia e Inovaçao (INETI), Estrada do Paço do Lumiar, 16049-038 Lisboa, Portugal","Muñoz, I., Departament de Química, Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona, 08193 Bellaterra, Barcelona, Spain; Peral, J., Departament de Química, Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona, 08193 Bellaterra, Barcelona, Spain; Antonio Ayllón, J., Departament de Química, Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona, 08193 Bellaterra, Barcelona, Spain; Malato, S., Plataforma Solar de Almería-CIEMAT, Carretera Senes km 4, 04200 Tabernas, Almería, Spain; Passarinho, P., Instituto Nacional de Engenharia, Tecnologia e Inovaçao (INETI), Estrada do Paço do Lumiar, 16049-038 Lisboa, Portugal; Domènech, X., Departament de Química, Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona, 08193 Bellaterra, Barcelona, Spain","A comparative life cycle assessment (LCA) of two solar-driven advanced oxidation processes, namely heterogeneous semiconductor photocatalysis and homogeneous photo-Fenton, both coupled to biological treatment, is carried out in order to identify the environmentally preferable alternative to treat industrial wastewaters containing non-biodegradable priority hazardous substances. The study is based on solar pilot plant tests using α-methyl-phenylglycine as a target substance. The LCA study is based on the experimental results obtained, along with data from an industrial-scale plant. The system under study includes production of the plant infrastructure, chemicals, electricity, transport of all these materials to the plant site, management of the spent catalyst by transport and landfilling, as well as treatment of the biodegradable effluent obtained in a conventional municipal wastewater treatment plant, and excess sludge treatment by incineration. Nine environmental impact categories are included in the LCA: global warming, ozone depletion, human toxicity, freshwater aquatic toxicity, photochemical ozone formation, acidification, eutrophication, energy consumption, and land use. The experimental results obtained in the pilot plant show that solar photo-Fenton is able to obtain a biodegradable effluent much faster than solar heterogeneous photocatalysis, implying that the latter would require a much larger solar collector area in an industrial application. The results of the LCA show that, an industrial wastewater treatment plant based on heterogeneous photocatalysis involves a higher environmental impact than the photo-Fenton alternative, which displays impact scores 80-90% lower in most impact categories assessed. These results are mainly due to the larger size of the solar collector field needed by the plant. © 2006 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","Biological coupling; Heterogeneous photocatalysis; Life cycle assessment; Pharmaceuticals; Photo-Fenton; Solar energy; Wastewater treatment","Biological coupling; Heterogeneous photocatalysis; Life cycle assessment; Drug products; Global warming; Oxidation; Photocatalysis; Solar collectors; Solar energy; Wastewater treatment; alpha methyl phenylglycine; amino acid derivative; unclassified drug; Drug products; Global warming; Oxidation; Photocatalysis; Solar collectors; Solar energy; Wastewater treatment; bioremediation; catalysis; environmental impact assessment; life cycle analysis; photosynthetically active radiation; water treatment; acidification; article; biodegradability; catalyst; chemical industry; dangerous goods; effluent; electricity; energy consumption; environmental factor; environmental impact; eutrophication; experimental design; Fenton reaction; greenhouse effect; incineration; land use; landfill; life cycle assessment; marine environment; oxidation; ozone layer; photocatalysis; photochemical smog; photochemistry; priority journal; scoring system; semiconductor; sludge treatment; solar energy; waste water management; water contamination; Biodegradation, Environmental; Catalysis; Glycine; Hydrogen Peroxide; Hydrogen-Ion Concentration; Industrial Waste; Iron; Oxidation-Reduction; Photochemistry; Semiconductors; Sensitivity and Specificity; Sewage; Water Pollutants, Chemical; Water Purification",,"Fenton's reagent; Glycine, 56-40-6; Hydrogen Peroxide, 7722-84-1; Industrial Waste; Iron, 7439-89-6; Sewage; Water Pollutants, Chemical; methyl phenylglycine, 26682-99-5",,,,"Andreozzi, R., Caprio, V., Insola, A., Marotta, R., Advanced oxidation processes (AOP) for water purification and recovery (1999) Catal. Today, 53, pp. 51-59; Azapagic, A., Clift, R., Life cycle assessment and multiobjective optimisation (1999) J. Cleaner Production, 7, pp. 135-143; Bauer, R., Fallmann, H., The photo-Fenton oxidation. A cheap and efficient wastewater treatment method (1997) Res. Chem. Intermediates, 23 (4), pp. 291-388; Blanco, J., Malato, S., (2003) Solar Detoxification, , UNESCO Publishing, France; Consoli, F., Allen, D., Boustead, I., de Oude, N., Fava, J., Franklin, W., Quay, B., Vigon, B., (1993) Guidelines for Life-Cycle Assessment: A Code of Practice. Society of Environmental Toxicology and Chemistry, , Brussels, Belgium; Fernández-Ibáñez, P., Blanco, J., Malato, S., de las Nieves, F.J., Application of the colloidal stability of TiO2 particles for recovery and reuse in solar photocatalysis (2003) Water Res., 37, pp. 3180-3188; Gernjak, W., Fuerhacker, M., Fernández-Ibáñez, P., Blanco, J., Malato, S., Solar photo-Fenton treatment-process parameters and process control (2006) Appl. Catal. B: Environ., 64, pp. 1